SIMPLE: groin
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: groin
<hw>groin</hw> <pr>(groin)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>groin</ets>, fr. <ets>grogner</ets> to grunt, L.
<ets>grunnire</ets>.]</ety> <def>The snout of a swine.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Groin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Groin
<hw>Groin</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>grogner</ets> to grunt,
grumble.]</ety> <def>To grunt to growl; to snarl; to murmur.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bears that <qex>groined</qex> coatinually.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Groin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Groin
<hw>Groin</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>grein</ets> distinction,
division, branch; akin to Sw. <ets>gren</ets>, branch, space between the
legs, Icel. <ets>greina</ets> to distinguish, divide, Sw.
<ets>grena</ets> to branch, straddle. Cf. <er>Grain</er> a
branch.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The line between the
lower part of the abdomen and the thigh, or the region of this line; the
inguen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The projecting solid angle formed
by the meeting of two vaults, growing more obtuse as it approaches the
summit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>The surface formed by two such
vaults.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A frame of woodwork across a beach to accumulate and
retain shingle.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Weale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Groin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Groin
<hw>Groin</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Groined</conjf> <pr>(groind)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Groining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>To fashion
into groins; to build with groins.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hand that rounded Peter's dome,⟦br⟧
And <qex>groined</qex> the aisles of Christian Rome,⟦br⟧
Wrought in a sad sincerity.</q> <rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Groined</ent>⟦br⟧
